        <h2>1970 <span class="badge badge-secondary">Scientific Research</span></h2>
        <p>The Language Analog Research Project begins at the Yerkes Primate Center. It is funded by NICHD and directed by Dr. Duane Rumbaugh who is the Associate Director of the Yerkes Primate Research Center. 
  2. There are initially two ape subjects, a baby orangutan (BJ) and a baby chimpanzee (Lana), both females.  The original room for the project is 8 x 10 feet. </p>
  <p>
  Upon a visit to a friend in Norman, Oklahoma. Dr. Sue notices a poster at the Un. of Oklahoma that is advertising lecture – to be presented by Dr. Fouts and a chimpanzee named Booee, who has learned American Sign Language for the Deaf. She attends the lecture and is startled to see a nonhuman producing gestures when show a bowl, a hat, a pipe, etc. Lecture attendees are invited to visit “the chimp farm” and learn more the following day. She does so, and learns of the 30 chimpanzees there all with different backgrounds. Some have been in circuses, some are from the wild, some have come from zoos, some from rodeos, some are being raised by humans, some live in a captive colony, some live on an island, etc. She is shocked at the differences between these various chimpanzees, their backgrounds, there housing conditions, etc. She also finds gibbons living on island, families of several different macaque species in enclosures, baboons, peacocks, and various other nonhumans just 20 minutes from the edge of town. She is allowed to return and assigned to teach Booee more ASL signs. Aware that the vast variety of nonhuman beings, especially some who appear to be acquiring language, is not to be found elsewhere and aware that at Harvard she would focus on pigeons and the relationship between their behavior and that of human beings, she decides to enroll at the University of Oklahoma and being Ph. D. studies there instead. Many question the wisdom of this decision noting that it will affect her job opportunities in the future. She remains firm – feeling that the there is much more to be learned from the living beings there, and that if she works hard, surely a job will be available somewhere.</p>
    <p>
     Dr. Savage-Rumbaugh begins her graduate program at the University of Oklahoma working chimpanzees Lucy, Booee, Bruno, Alle and Wahsoe who are acquiring sign language under different rearing conditions as well as  with Petal, Pampy, Carrie, Shadrack, Meshak, Mimi, and Manny – chimpanzees being reared by their natural mothers in a mother-infant group. Her focus is upon language and nonverbal behavior in apes, as a function of differential rearing environments. 
  </p>
