        <h2>1975 <span class="badge badge-secondary">Scientific Research</span></h2>
        <p>Dr. Savage-Rumbaugh completes her dissertation “Mother-Infant Behavior Among Captive Group-Living Chimpanzees”  Un. of Oklahoma. This study documented many deliberate intentional nonverbal signals, devised between mother and infant chimpanzees. </p>
        <p> Dr. Sue” is awarded a post-doctoral fellowship from George State University by Dr. Duane Rumbaugh to do research at the Yerkes Primate Center. She arrives  just shortly after the bonobos are released from quarantine. Five bonobos were imported and two dies during the quarantine period. She is the first behavioral scientist to work in the tradition of the ethological framework at the Yerkes Main Center. She is also assigned to assist as a comparative psychologist and  learning theorist in the Lana language lab under the direction of Dr. Duane Rumbaugh.</p>
        <p>The bonobos are brought to the Yerkes Primate Center on a Lend Lease Agreement with the Congo. The funding comes from the ONR. The Director of the Yerkes Center at that time is a former British Double Agent and the Assistant Director is a former 3 star General in the Army.  Yerkes (at that time) was staffed by German neuro-scientists.</p>
