        <h2>2003 <span class="badge badge-secondary">History</span></h2>
        <p>The City of Des Moines loans 200 acres to IPLS with the provision that it be employed for the housing of nonhuman primates and associated educational activities.  The lend lease agreement states that should the project fail the land will be returned to the City of Des Moines.</p>
        <p>The parcel of land was selected from seven parcels offered by the city. At that I was not told that the land was in a flood plain.  I was aware that the land was near the river, however it was bounded by a levy.  I was told that the levy would prevent flooding.</p>
        <p>The land was donated by the city, in a lend lease agreement. The agreement specified that a facility would be constructed for ape and that should the project fail, the buildings and the land would revert to the city.</p>
        <p>Initial building meetings with architects are held and the first building plan is presented.  At these planning meetings I learn the land is in a flood plain. Mr. Lovins of the Rocky Mountain Institute attended this meeting accompanied by someone who was familiar with flood plains. This expert argued strongly and forcefully against building in the current location, because it was a recognized flood plain.  According to this expert, the location would flood and we could not avoid this happening at some point. In addition he argued that the sandy substrate would not prove suitable for a facility and that the substrate could shift over time as underwater pathways carved new channels underground. This expert was overruled by the architects. They assured  me that it was possible to build up a pad which would keep the building out of the flood plain. Following this meeting, I traveld to Omaha to work with the architects and the building is redesigned specifically to accomplish the needs of the research trajectory. </p>
        <p>Following this meeting Mr.Townsend, myself, Mr. Fields and Mr. Brocker met with NICH officials in Washington to describe the planned location of the Language Research Center to the Iowa Primate Learning Sanctuary in Des Moines.</p>
        <p>Mr. Townsend decides to invite an orangutan project from the Smithsonian to also relocate to Iowa. </p>
        <p>A second building is begun for the orangutans and is completed before bonobo facility. The orangutan project is led by Dr. Ben Beck, joining his team are Dr. Rob Shumaker, Dr. Karyl Swartz.</p>
        <p>Mr. Al Setka is named PR director for the project. (Mr. Setka is a current member of the Ape Initiative board).</p>
        <p>The name Great Ape Trust is adopted as the public named for IPLS. Mr. Brocker is named Project Director. </p>
        <p>The bonobo building design is feature in a leading architectural magazine and it architect Peter Hinde is awarded an excellence in design.  The building is represented as Lead's certified building. Amory Lovins  points out that it is in a flood plain and needs to be relocated.</p>
        <p>After the above meeting Mr. Townsend and Mr. Broker announced that they were going to the Smithsonian National Zoological Society to meet with Dr.'s Shumaker and Beck regarding the relocation of their project to the Iowa Primate Learning Sanctuary.  We were not invited to that meeting, even though the ostensive purpose of that meeting was to convince Dr.'s Beck and Shoemaker to join the facility being constructed in Des Moines.</p>
        <p>Mr. Townsend and Mr. Brocker travelled to Des Moines after meeting with Dr.'s Shumaker and Beck. The indicated the following:
          a) that the bonobo facility was going to be downsized by half
          b) that an orangutan facility was going to be constructed
          c) that the bonobos facility should contain a large classroom and that I was to focus on 
          teaching exercises daily in that classroom, with the bonobos as backdrop.
          I stated that in my view was that this would significantly interfere with the research and I could not approve placing a large classroom in the middle of the bonobo facility. In response to that statement Mr. Townsend indicated that I must then submit a grant immediately to NICHD to cover the research costs. Prior to that time, the plan had been to complete the facility and to get the research up and running before resubmitting to NIHCD.  This had been advised by the Peggy McCardle when we met with her in Washington DC, just prior to Mr. Townsend's meeting with Dr. Shoemaker and Beck. I agree to submit the grant through GSU as per Mr. Townsend's instructions, however I indicate to him that a grant for work in a facility not yet construction will have zero probability of getting funded. This fact is of no concern to Mr. Townsend or to Mr. Brocker. 
          </p>
          <p>The architect of the bonobo building resigned from the Leo A. Daily firm shortly thereafter. The building was downsized by more than a factor of two. It appeared to have been redesigned more or less by a computer than by a architect, as the downsizing was done by halving rather than redesigning.  The new architect was unfamiliar with the research needs and/or the research trajectory.  The new architect designed a second building which was to used to house orangutans from the Smithsonian Zoo. It was a square slab building. </p>
