        <h2>2004 <span class="badge badge-secondary">History</span></h2>
        <p>The grant to NICHD is denied. The reason given is that Dr. Sue has structured the planned proposals around the design of a facility that is not yet constructed. She is invited to resubmit the grant, once the facility is actually in place. </p>
        <p>The orangutans Inda and Azy are relocated to Iowa, followed in 6 months by the bonobos, Matata, P-suke, Kanzi, Panbanisha, Nathan, Nyota, Maisha and Elykia. </p>

        <p>The construction of the orangutan building began first. It was to be completed first and the orangutans were to be relocated before the bonobos. The explanation given for the orangutans receiving first priority was that Dr. Shumaker's demonstration project at the Smithsonian been given a termination date by the Smithsonian Zoo. He needed to move quickly. In addition Dr. Beck had been removed from the Smithsonian faculty because he was deemed responsible for the death of two red pandas. The pandas died because a exterminator placed materials in their cage designed to kill rodents and the pandas ate these materials. Dr. Beck was responsible for the hiring and supervisor of the exterminators.  </p>
        <p>
          GSU gave a drop-dead date by which the bonobo building had to be completed or the bonobos would go to a zoo. The delay in receiving the bonobos, due to placing the orangutan building as the first priority on the list caused David Washburn, the new director of the Language Research Center (LRC) great concern. He so expressed this to Mr. Fields, though not directly to me.  It was relayed to me and I therefore began to try to speed up the construction of the bonobos building. The drop dead date was the Spring of 2005. 
        </p>
        <p>Dr. Sue moves to Iowa during last 8 months of completion of the bonobo building.  Upon arrival she learns that time Dr. Shoemaker and Dr. Beck were making extensive changes in the bonobos building. They are redesigning the bonobo to house gorillas. They  have been given the rights to "sign off" on the various stages of the bonobo plan, rather me, by the CEO Mr. Brocker. With the redesigns underway two things were occurring a) the building was being changed toward a zoological facility and away from a research facility and b) it was being modified to house gorillas not bonobos. </p>
        <p>Dr. Sue  requests that 'sign off' rights on the construction plans be returned to her, as I she is now on site. She also requests that many of the modifications planned for gorillas be retracted. She requests that construction of the bonobo building be given higher priority so that the building would meet the GSU anticipated timeline. She goes directly to Mr. Townsend to request these alterations and her requests are accepted.</p>
        <p>The PR director (Al Setka) and a PR firm that he has hired, informed us that a name and image change for the facility was underway.   Dr. Shumaker and Dr. Beck have had chosen a new name for the facility. It was now going to be called the "Great Ape Station," rather than the Iowa Primate Learning Sanctuary. We are also informed that Dr. Beck was arranging for gorillas to be brought to the facility and that Dr. Shoemaker was arranging for 30 to 40 chimpanzees to be housed there in the future. We were told that we must join the AZA and meet their requirements. (The AZA had previously objected to the bonobo research because it rejected, in principle, human/ape interaction, except in the sanctuary of Claudine Andree in Kinshasa.) The name change marked a turn toward establishing a zoological part, and away from establishing a research facility.  Dr. Duane Rumbaugh  strongly objected to the naming the facility "GAS," and to the requirement that we had to join the AZA. Following months of debate, Mr. Townsend selected the name Great Ape Trust.</p>
        <p>Dr. Shoemaker and his "research team," Dr. Beck, Dr. Swartz and Dr. Wick were all relocated to Iowa. </p>
        <p>Mr. Potter, the lawyer hired by Mr. Townsend to make certain that all the orangutans and bonobos were properly transferred to GAS/IPLS, requests a private meeting with Dr. Rumbaugh and myself. At that meeting, he indicates that Dr. Beck and Dr. Shoemaker are planning to remove me not long after the bonobos are relocated to Georgia and that these plans were made in collaboration with the Atlanta Zoo, who was claiming that it owned Matata, Elykia and Maisha.  However it did not own either one, and neither one had ever been housed at the zoo. In fact, no bonobos had ever been housed at the Atlanta Zoo. The Zoo was claiming that Yerkes had transferred Matata to the Zoo and that Matsuzawa of Japan transferred P-Suke to Matata.  Later it indicated that it was willing to trade the bonobos it owned for gorillas, after the bonobos were  were relocated to Iowa. Phase one of the plane was to remove me and phase two of the plan was to move the bonobos to Zoo Atlanta. </p>
        <h2>2004 <span class="badge badge-secondary">Administrative</span></h2>
        <p>Jared was invited to move to Iowa and is offered a full salaried position by Mr. Townsend. He decline and accepts instead, Post-doc position to work with Dr. Hopkins at Emory. Dr. Hopkins was conducting MRI scans of ape brains and Dr. Taglialatela wished to learn how to do MRI research.</p>
        <p>The Orangutan building is completed and the orangutans are relocated to Iowa.</p>
