    <div class="time-container time-right">
      <div class="time-content">
        <h2>2008 <span class="badge badge-secondary">History</span></h2>
        <p>Mr. Townsend offered me a contract to sign that would allow me to return but with very limited access.</p>
        <p>I returned  to find that the bonobos had been generally kept apart, especially the males as a matter of policy by Elizabert Pugh. Because of this, the males were constantly fighting through the mesh. I had never encountered such behaviors in this group (or any bonobo group) prior to my removal.</p>
        <p>I returned and I was given more access. I was not permitted to direct anyone, to teach anyone or to work closely with anyone.  I was not permitted to collect data because Rob's students and staff and graduate students working under Fields are given first priority.</p>
        <p>Nyota asked to go in and visit Kanzi. I had not told that Kanzi and Nyota had been kept apart during my absence. When Kanzi entered, he displayed at Panbanisha and passed by pushing her. This upset Nyota who bit Kanzi on the foot. He appeared to break his mandible during this bite. The mandible was repaired however the dentists indicated that he was still likely to loose his upper right canine, which did later occur. Prior to this,  Nyota had never bitten another bonobo. He also do not participate in play-biting as do other bonobos.  It appeared that Nyota did not have the knowledge of how to bite that bonobos gain through play biting. </p>
        <p>Takashi, whom the bonobos have know for at least 10 years, was removed as staff supervisor and replaced by Tyler. This change resulted in further disorganization within the bonobo group and an increasing separation between the daily world of the staff, their communications with the bonobos and the world of the bonobos. Tyler was the newest person in the lab, having been there only a year. He lacked the respect and the trust of the bonobos. In fact, the bonobos detested Tyler.</p>
        <p>Kanzi did not approve of this or of the appointment of the new supervisor, nor of the demotion of Takashi. When I indicated to Kanzi that we are going to have to do what Tyler told us to do, Kanzi bite me on the mouth. (This is the first and only time that Kanzi has bitten me.)</p>
        <p>GSU veterinary staff visited the day that I told Kanzi we were going to have to do as Tylor requested.  I was asked to make a presentation to this group regarding the research.  Following the presentation these veterinarian indicated to visitors at the laboratory that the bite on my mouth was a herpes lesion and that I had obtained this lesion from Kanzi.  From the appointment of  Tyler to the position of supervisor, rumors such as this regarding my interactions with the bonobos, began to flood the lab on a regular basis.  With the appointment of Tyler as staff in place, Mr. Fields began the process of obtaining "Animal Assurances."  These were documents, provided by ALAW, to certify that the laboratory had met strict training and over-site practices. An ALAW "animal assurance" number was required before a grant to do research with animals could go forward.</p>
        <p>The building flooded with 5 feet of water on June 8.  All power was shut off and the building was accessible only by boat. The bonobos survive by staying in the tunnels that were designed to connect the caging. During this period, essentially all feeding and care is performed by Liz Pugh and myself. The staff are present to help move items out of the building and to bring food into the building however they do stay in the flood waters. The water as reported to be highly toxic and we are asked to keep the bonobos out of them. There is no way to do this other than to explain to the bonobos that they should not be in the water because they are toxic and to ask them to stay away from the water and to confine themselves to the small tunnels. The bonobos are nonresponsive to the requests to do so by the staff, but they do attend to the requests and explanation made by myself and by Liz Pugh, daily, in this regard.</p>
        <p>
           The bonobo staff will not care for bonobos under the dangerous flood conditions so Dr. Savage-Rumbaugh and her sister Ms. Liz Pugh care for the bonobos 24/7 for two weeks. During the following months bonobo Nathan and Ms. Pugh develop cancer. Both were in the dangerous flood waters far more than the other bonobos or than Dr. Savage-Rumbaugh. 
        </p>
        <p>Nathan and Liz Pugh developed cancer 3 to 6 months after the flood. They were the two individuals most exposed to the flood water. Nathan was more exposed than the other bonobos because he was the youngest and he kept wanting to play in the water. He was the least likely to listen to our explanations of why the bonobos had to stay out of the water because he was the least able to comprehend them. Liz was the person in the water the most because the Trust provided inadequate waders and she was constantly wet. She also spent the most time with Nathan attempting to convince him to go out of the water and to stay out of the water. I purchased my own waders and was thus protected from the water. I do so because I considered the waders provided by the Trust to be inadequate.</p>
        <p>Zoo Atlanta claims ownership of Matata and Maisha and requests their return to Atlanta. Mr. Fields asks them to provide ownership documents which they fail to  provide.
        </p>
